<subSubSection id="FD9102D0ED13FF93FF04F825FDB3FF7E" lastPageId="3" lastPageNumber="154" pageId="1" pageNumber="152" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="B534515BED13FF92FF04F825FA9DFE79" blockId="1.[151,1437,1939,2038]" lastBlockId="2.[151,1436,151,465]" lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="153" pageId="1" pageNumber="152">
<emphasis id="87FF8D49ED13FF91FF04F825FE90F805" bold="true" box="[151,274,1939,1965]" pageId="1" pageNumber="152">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="728B2AD8ED13FF91FE84F825FE0FF805" authorityName="Thorell" authorityYear="1895" box="[279,397,1939,1965]" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Charippus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="1" pageNumber="152" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="87FF8D49ED13FF91FE84F825FE0FF805" box="[279,397,1939,1965]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="152">Charippus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
resembles 
<taxonomicName id="728B2AD8ED13FF91FD9BF822FC9FF805" authority="Keyserling, 1882" authorityName="Keyserling" authorityYear="1882" box="[520,797,1939,1966]" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Cytaea" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="1" pageNumber="152" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="87FF8D49ED13FF91FD9BF822FDD5F806" box="[520,599,1940,1966]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="152">Cytaea</emphasis>
Keyserling, 
<quantity id="7273FCBEED13FF91FD76F825FC9FF805" box="[741,797,1939,1965]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.780279999999999" pageId="1" pageNumber="152" unit="in" value="1882.0">1882</quantity>
</taxonomicName>
in genitalic structures such as the wide embolic spiral and the highly coiled copulatory ducts, but it can be distinguished by: (1) the presence of dense pits on the carapace (
<figureCitation id="2DB04DDEED13FF91FAFCF801FF36F85D" captionStart="FIGURES 11–16" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1021,1045]" captionTargetBox="[157,1430,187,997]" captionTargetId="figure-19@4.[157,1430,181,997]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 11–16. Charippus asper Yu, Maddison &amp; Zhang, sp. nov., male (11, 14) and female (12–13, 15–16). 11–13. Habitus, in dorsal (11–12) and lateral (13) view, arrow pointing to dense pits on cephalon; 14–15. Front view of carapace; 16. Details of left chelicera, back view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6500743" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6500743/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="152">Fig. 11</figureCitation>
); (2) the presence of two centre-parted setal bands (CPSB, 
<figureCitation id="2DB04DDEED13FF91FCD4F86DFC28F85D" box="[839,938,2011,2037]" captionStart="FIGURES 195–200" captionStartId="39.[151,264,1967,1991]" captionTargetBox="[159,1428,181,1943]" captionTargetId="figure-19@39.[159,1428,181,1943]" captionTargetPageId="39" captionText="FIGURES 195–200. Living female of Charippus yinae Wang &amp; Li, 2020 (© Weihang Wang)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6500850" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6500850/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="152">Figs 196</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="2DB04DDEED13FF91FC26F86DFC63F85E" box="[949,993,2011,2038]" captionStart="FIGURES 214–220" captionStartId="42.[151,264,1576,1600]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,344,1553]" captionTargetId="figure-91@42.[151,1436,344,1553]" captionTargetPageId="42" captionText="FIGURES 214–220. Living males of Charippus yunnanensis (Cao &amp; Li, 2016) comb. nov. (© Weihang Wang). 214–217, 219–220. Adult; 218. Subadult." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6500857" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6500857/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="152">216</figureCitation>
) on the cephalon (except for 
<taxonomicName id="728B2AD8ED13FF92FAB5F86DFE95FF18" authority="Yu &amp; Wang &amp; Maddison &amp; Zhang, 2022" authorityName="Yu &amp; Wang &amp; Maddison &amp; Zhang" authorityYear="2022" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Charippus" kingdom="Animalia" lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="153" order="Araneae" pageId="1" pageNumber="152" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="minotaurus" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="87FF8D49ED13FF92FAB5F86DFE95FF18" italics="true" lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="153" pageId="1" pageNumber="152">Charippus minotaurus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="87FF8D49ED10FF92FE8CFF21FEF8FF19" bold="true" box="[287,378,151,177]" pageId="2" pageNumber="153">
<taxonomicNameLabel id="9CCC3032ED10FF92FE8CFF21FEF8FF19" box="[287,378,151,177]" pageId="2" pageNumber="153" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
); (3) the absence of the crescent-shaped white band at the posterior edge of carapace; (4) the presence of lateral depressions (LD, 
<figureCitation id="2DB04DDEED10FF92FDA6FF0DFD04FF7D" box="[565,646,187,213]" captionStart="FIGURES 23–29" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1933,1957]" captionTargetBox="[153,1433,181,1898]" captionTargetId="figure-19@6.[153,1433,181,1909]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 23–29. Female genitalia of Charippus asper sp. nov.. 23–25, 27. Ventral view; 26, 28. Dorsal view; 29. CD path." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6500751" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6500751/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="153">Fig. 27</figureCitation>
) near the copulatory openings of epigynum; (5) the edge of lamina of embolic disc (LED) is serrulate in most species (
<figureCitation id="2DB04DDEED10FF92FD23FF69FC87FF51" box="[688,773,223,249]" captionStart="FIGURES 20–22" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1972,1996]" captionTargetBox="[272,1311,1200,1948]" captionTargetId="figure-44@5.[272,1316,1198,1948]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 20–22. Palp of Charippus asper Yu, Maddison &amp; Zhang, sp. nov., in prolateral (20), ventral (21) and retrolateral (22) view, arrow pointing to the denticles on embolic base." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6500749" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6500749/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="153">Figs 21</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="2DB04DDEED10FF92FC83FF69FCACFF51" box="[784,814,223,249]" captionStart="FIGURES 36–38" captionStartId="8.[151,264,1034,1058]" captionTargetBox="[298,1286,181,1011]" captionTargetId="figure-19@8.[285,1303,181,1011]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURES 36–38. Palp of Charippus bukittimah Yu, Maddison &amp; Zhang, sp. nov., in prolateral (36), ventral (37) and retrolateral (38) view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6500759" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6500759/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="153">37</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="2DB04DDEED10FF92FCAAFF69FCDAFF52" box="[825,856,223,250]" captionStart="FIGURES 61–65" captionStartId="12.[151,264,1882,1906]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1858]" captionTargetId="figure-19@12.[151,1436,181,1858]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURES 61–65. Palp of Charippus callainus Yu, Maddison &amp; Zhang, sp. nov.. 61. Expanded bulb; 62–65. Palp in ventral (62), prolateral (63), retrolateral (64) and dorsal (65) view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6500780" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6500780/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="153">61</figureCitation>
). In 
<taxonomicName id="728B2AD8ED10FF92FC1AFF69FC5AFF51" authorityName="Keyserling" authorityYear="1882" box="[905,984,223,249]" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Cytaea" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="2" pageNumber="153" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="87FF8D49ED10FF92FC1AFF69FC5AFF51" box="[905,984,223,249]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="153">Cytaea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the carapace lacks dense pits and CPSB, and has a crescent-shaped white band on the posterior edge; the epigynum lacks LD; the edge of LED of the male palp is not serrulate (see 
<bibRefCitation id="D11A2CAAED10FF92FE2BFE91FD59FEE9" author="Zhang, J. &amp; Maddison, W. P." box="[440,731,294,321]" pageId="2" pageNumber="153" pagination="1 - 147" refId="ref13808" refString="Zhang, J. &amp; Maddison, W. P. (2015) Genera of euophryine jumping spiders (Araneae: Salticidae), with a combined molecularmorphological phylogeny. Zootaxa, 3938 (1), 1 - 147. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 3938.1.1" type="journal article" year="2015">Zhang &amp; Maddison 2015</bibRefCitation>
, figs 545–551). 
<taxonomicName id="728B2AD8ED10FF92FC05FE91FB8EFEE9" authorityName="Thorell" authorityYear="1895" box="[918,1036,295,321]" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Charippus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="2" pageNumber="153" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="87FF8D49ED10FF92FC05FE91FB8EFEE9" box="[918,1036,295,321]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="153">Charippus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
resembles 
<taxonomicName id="728B2AD8ED10FF92FB1DFE91FAFCFEE9" authority="Simon, 1889" authorityName="Simon" authorityYear="1889" box="[1166,1406,295,321]" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Laufeia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="2" pageNumber="153" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="87FF8D49ED10FF92FB1DFE91FB66FEE9" box="[1166,1252,295,321]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="153">Laufeia</emphasis>
Simon, 
<quantity id="7273FCBEED10FF92FAD5FE91FAFCFEE9" box="[1350,1406,295,321]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.79806" pageId="2" pageNumber="153" unit="in" value="1889.0">1889</quantity>
</taxonomicName>
in color pattern, body form and the bicuspid retromarginal tooth of chelicera, but it can be distinguished by the large embolic disc along with a long and coiled embolus (
<figureCitation id="2DB04DDEED10FF92FD44FED9FCB4FE21" box="[727,822,367,393]" captionStart="FIGURES 113–115" captionStartId="22.[151,264,1961,1985]" captionTargetBox="[152,1428,1165,1936]" captionTargetId="figure-62@22.[151,1437,1153,1937]" captionTargetPageId="22" captionText="FIGURES 113–115. Palp of Charippus heishiding Yu, Maddison &amp; Zhang, sp. nov., holotype, in ventral (114), prolateral (113) and retrolateral (115) view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6500807" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6500807/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="153">Fig. 114</figureCitation>
), the highly coiled copulatory ducts, and the absence of secondary spermathecae (
<figureCitation id="2DB04DDEED10FF92FE24FE25FD9BFE05" box="[439,537,403,429]" captionStart="FIGURES 119–123" captionStartId="24.[151,264,1918,1942]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,345,1888]" captionTargetId="figure-71@24.[151,1436,345,1895]" captionTargetPageId="24" captionText="FIGURES 119–123. Female genitalia of Charippus heishiding Yu, Maddison &amp; Zhang, sp. nov.. 119, 121. Ventral view; 120, 122. Dorsal view; 123. CD path." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6500813" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6500813/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="153">Fig. 122</figureCitation>
); vs. the embolus is short and blunt, the copulatory ducts are relatively short and not obviously coiled, and the secondary spermathecae are present in 
<taxonomicName id="728B2AD8ED10FF92FC0BFE01FC6CFE79" authorityName="Simon" authorityYear="1889" box="[920,1006,439,465]" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Laufeia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="2" pageNumber="153" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="87FF8D49ED10FF92FC0BFE01FC6CFE79" box="[920,1006,439,465]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="153">Laufeia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(see 
<bibRefCitation id="D11A2CAAED10FF92FBBAFE01FB2BFE79" author="Ikeda, H." box="[1065,1193,439,465]" pageId="2" pageNumber="153" pagination="37 - 43" refId="ref12997" refString="Ikeda, H. (1998) Spiders of the genus Laufeia (Araneae: Salticidae) from Japan. Acta Arachnologica, 47 (1), 37 - 43." type="journal article" year="1998">Ikeda 1998</bibRefCitation>
, figs 5–8).
</paragraph>
<caption id="E1F401D3ED10FF92FF04F8DCFDACF847" ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6500739" ID-Zenodo-Dep="6500739" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6500739/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="153" startId="2.[151,264,1898,1922]" targetBox="[221,1366,489,1875]" targetPageId="2">
<paragraph id="B534515BED10FF92FF04F8DCFDACF847" blockId="2.[151,1436,1898,2031]" pageId="2" pageNumber="153">
<emphasis id="87FF8D49ED10FF92FF04F8DCFEB9F82A" bold="true" box="[151,315,1898,1922]" pageId="2" pageNumber="153">FIGURES 1–6.</emphasis>
Habitats of 
<taxonomicName id="728B2AD8ED10FF92FE2AF8DCFDD5F82A" box="[441,599,1898,1922]" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Charippus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="2" pageNumber="153" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis id="87FF8D49ED10FF92FE2AF8DCFDA6F82A" box="[441,548,1898,1922]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="153">Charippus</emphasis>
spp.
</taxonomicName>
, with arrows pointing to where the specimens were collected. 1–2. 
<taxonomicName id="728B2AD8ED10FF92FA95F8DDFE84F80F" authority="Wang &amp; Li, 2020" authorityName="Wang &amp; Li" authorityYear="2020" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Charippus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="2" pageNumber="153" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="yinae">
<emphasis id="87FF8D49ED10FF92FA95F8DDFAD9F82A" box="[1286,1371,1899,1922]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="153">C. yinae</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="D11A2CAAED10FF92FAF1F8DDFE84F80F" author="Wang, C. &amp; Li, S. Q." pageId="2" pageNumber="153" pagination="43 - 69" refId="ref13394" refString="Wang, C. &amp; Li, S. Q. (2020) Seven new species of jumping spiders (Araneae, Salticidae) from Xishuangbanna, China. ZooKeys, 968, 43 - 69. https: // doi. org / 10.3897 / zookeys. 968.55047" type="journal article" year="2020">Wang &amp; Li, 2020</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
in XTBG (1) and leprosy village (type locality, 2), Yunnan, China; 3. 
<taxonomicName id="728B2AD8ED10FF92FC55F839FAC0F80E" authority="Yu, Maddison &amp; Zhang" authorityName="Yu, Maddison &amp; Zhang" authorityYear="2022" box="[966,1346,1934,1959]" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Charippus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="2" pageNumber="153" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="heishiding" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="87FF8D49ED10FF92FC55F839FBCFF80E" box="[966,1101,1934,1958]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="153">C. heishiding</emphasis>
Yu, Maddison &amp; Zhang
</taxonomicName>
, 
<emphasis id="87FF8D49ED10FF92FADFF839FA1EF80F" bold="true" box="[1356,1436,1935,1959]" pageId="2" pageNumber="153">
<taxonomicNameLabel id="9CCC3032ED10FF92FADFF839FA1EF80F" box="[1356,1436,1935,1959]" pageId="2" pageNumber="153" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
in Fengkai, Guangdong, China; 4. 
<taxonomicName id="728B2AD8ED10FF92FE61F805FCBFF862" authority="Yu, Maddison &amp; Zhang" authorityName="Yu, Maddison &amp; Zhang" authorityYear="2022" box="[498,829,1970,1995]" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Charippus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="2" pageNumber="153" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="denjii" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="87FF8D49ED10FF92FE61F805FDCBF862" box="[498,585,1970,1994]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="153">C. denjii</emphasis>
Yu, Maddison &amp; Zhang
</taxonomicName>
, 
<emphasis id="87FF8D49ED10FF92FCD5F805FC14F863" bold="true" box="[838,918,1971,1995]" pageId="2" pageNumber="153">
<taxonomicNameLabel id="9CCC3032ED10FF92FCD5F805FC14F863" box="[838,918,1971,1995]" pageId="2" pageNumber="153" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
in Wuzhishan, Hainan, China; 5–6. 
<taxonomicName id="728B2AD8ED10FF92FA91F805FEC5F846" authority="(Cao &amp; Li, 2016)" authorityName="Yu &amp; Wang &amp; Maddison &amp; Zhang" authorityYear="2022" baseAuthorityName="Cao &amp; Li" baseAuthorityYear="2016" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Cytaea" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="2" pageNumber="153" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="yunnanensis" status="comb. nov.">
<emphasis id="87FF8D49ED10FF92FA91F805FA1EF862" box="[1282,1436,1971,1994]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="153">C. yunnanensis</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="D11A2CAAED10FF92FF0DF861FEC2F846" author="Cao, Q. &amp; Li, S. Q. &amp; Zabka, M." box="[158,320,2006,2031]" pageId="2" pageNumber="153" pagination="43 - 104" refId="ref12943" refString="Cao, Q., Li, S. Q. &amp; Zabka, M. (2016) The jumping spiders from Xishuangbanna, Yunnan, China (Araneae, Salticidae). ZooKeys, 630, 43 - 104. https: // doi. org / 10.3897 / zookeys. 630.8466" type="journal article" year="2016">Cao &amp; Li, 2016</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="87FF8D49ED10FF92FEDEF861FE43F847" bold="true" box="[333,449,2007,2031]" pageId="2" pageNumber="153">
<taxonomicNameLabel id="9CCC3032ED10FF92FEDEF861FE43F847" box="[333,449,2007,2031]" pageId="2" pageNumber="153" rank="species">comb. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
in XTBG.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph id="B534515BED11FF93FF54FF21FDB3FF7E" blockId="3.[151,1436,150,249]" pageId="3" pageNumber="154">
<emphasis id="87FF8D49ED11FF93FF54FF21FE04FF18" bold="true" box="[199,390,150,177]" pageId="3" pageNumber="154">Natural history.</emphasis>
Specimens of 
<taxonomicName id="728B2AD8ED11FF93FDBCFF21FD27FF19" authorityName="Thorell" authorityYear="1895" box="[559,677,151,177]" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Charippus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="3" pageNumber="154" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="87FF8D49ED11FF93FDBCFF21FD27FF19" box="[559,677,151,177]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="154">Charippus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
have been found mainly on tree trunks, but also sometimes on dry sticks or surface of rocks (
<figureCitation id="2DB04DDEED11FF93FE2DFF0DFDA6FF7E" box="[446,548,187,214]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–6" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1898,1922]" captionTargetBox="[221,1366,489,1875]" captionTargetId="figure-190@2.[221,1366,489,1875]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–6. Habitats of Charippus spp., with arrows pointing to where the specimens were collected. 1–2. C. yinae Wang &amp; Li, 2020 in XTBG (1) and leprosy village (type locality, 2), Yunnan, China; 3. C. heishiding Yu, Maddison &amp; Zhang, sp. nov. in Fengkai, Guangdong, China; 4. C. denjii Yu, Maddison &amp; Zhang, sp. nov. in Wuzhishan, Hainan, China; 5–6. C. yunnanensis (Cao &amp; Li, 2016) comb. nov. in XTBG." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6500739" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6500739/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="154">Figs 1–6</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
